>>67088828
For your first story go with something small and self contained as opposed to some sprawling epic. The story archive is full of stories made by inexperienced authors who had a really good idea for a story, made a chapter or two, then promptly lost the motivation/will/creative spark/whatever to bring their idea to life. So in terms of structure try to have just a few major story beats in total and aim for a word count of ten thousand or less, though it's a very soft limit. I wouldn't say there's a minimum word count since even stories only a few hundred words long can be satisfying to read

>>67088828
>What's a good word count to aim for
Don't do this. Not a single short story I've ever written took word count into consideration. If I had a minimum I had to reach I'd check after it was done and that's it.
>Mainly trying to avoid the feeling of "this could've been greentext"
Understandable, so for this I'd just go "more than 2000" words, which is what a lot of people write a day. Is that a good milestone for you?

>>67092116
>leave the setting and story open for expansion
Frankly? You can, but you have to be careful not to start injecting all your cool ideas into that first story and keep it lean and tight. You can have thoughts and ambitions, what you can't have is a shitload of little dead-ends unless you're an established name. I mean, you can, but people will wonder if you're just sloppy and it won't look very good. (I tried this once upon a time) Even if I were a much bigger name than I am now I would keep things as neat and tidy as possible.

So, building the setting... I'd say that maybe you could introduce a character you want to use elsewhere, or describe a place or thing that serves as a springboard somewhere else. Think of your average bar entry scene, the character scans side to side to take in the scene, the patrons, the music, the style, some shit on the walls that catches their eye, and whatever else. All of those things are now props to use elsewhere, but they're not going to leave a reader wondering why you brought them up. Why? You're describing the bar. Hiding your ties to other stories in these places works.
